<CHARACTERISTICS_OF_STUDIES MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:36:38 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<CHARACTERISTICS_OF_INCLUDED_STUDIES MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:36:38 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" SORT_BY="STUDY" USER_DEF_1_ENABLED="NO" USER_DEF_2_ENABLED="NO" USER_DEF_3_ENABLED="NO">
<INCLUDED_CHAR MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:30:35 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" STUDY_ID="STD-Dolgin-1997">
<CHAR_METHODS>
<P>Objective: To evaluate the effects of a structured group intervention on the knowledge, feelings, attitudes, and mood states of school-aged and adolescent siblings of childhood cancer patients.</P>
<P>Study design: before and after.</P>
<P>Recruitment: consecutive sample.</P>
<P>Allocation: N/A</P>
<P>Informed consent: consent of parents and assent of sibling-participant.</P>
<P>Total number approached: 27</P>
<P>Number recruited: 24.</P>
<P>Method of analysis: paired t-test. </P>
<P>Follow-up: 95.84%<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_METHODS>
<CHAR_PARTICIPANTS MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:30:11 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Country: Israel.</P>
<P>Clinical setting: children's hospital.</P>
<P>Inclusions: (1) a sibling currently in active treatment or within 6 months of treatment; (2) sibling-participant was aware of child-patient's diagnosis of cancer; (3) consent of parent and assent of sibling-participant; (4) sibling-participant between 6 and 18 years of age.</P>
<P>Exclusions: logistically unable to attend group meetings or parent or child refusal.</P>
<P>Healthy siblings of children with the following diagnoses: leukaemia (37.5%), Hodgkins Lymphoma (12.5%), Ewing's Sarcoma (12.5%), Rhabdomyosarcoma (8.3%), Neuroblastoma (8.3%), brain tumour (8.3%), Non-Hodgkins Lymphoma (8.3%).</P>
<P>Age: 7 to 17 (mean: 11.71).</P>
<P>Gender: male: n = 12, female: n = 11.</P>
<P>Ethnicity: not stated.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<CHAR_INTERVENTIONS MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:30:30 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Aims: not stated.</P>
<P>Participants were divided into two age-groups: the children's group (ages 7 to 11 years; n = 13), and the adolescent group (ages 12 to 17 years; n = 11).</P>
<P>Participants attended 6 group sessions held on consecutive weeks. The sessions were facilitated by a clinical social worker, a child life specialist, and a supervising psychologist. Sessions were informal and held in a meeting room away from the hospital ward. In addition to group discussions concerning their experience of the illness and its impact, participants took part in arts and crafts and other creative activities in order to encourage interaction and promote non-verbal expression. Each session emphasised different aspects of siblings' experience of their brother or sister's cancer.<BR/>The content of the Intervention was based on responses to structured interviews.</P>
<P>N = (baseline) 24.</P>
<P>Theoretical basis: not stated.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_INTERVENTIONS>
<CHAR_OUTCOMES MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:30:35 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Timing of outcome assessment: 2 weeks preceding the 1st group meeting and 6-8 weeks after the final group meeting.</P>
<P>Knowledge and understanding: of paediatric cancer and treatment was measured by the Cancer-Related Knowledge questionnaire (Carpenter 1990);</P>
<P>Coping, adjustment and wellbeing were measured by the Feelings and Attitudes Questionnaire (Sahler and Carpenter 1989), which is divided into sections on Interpersonal Problems, Intrapsychic Preoccupation, Disease-Related Communication, and Fear.</P>
<P>Current mood state was measured by the Mood Questionnaire (Sahler and Carpenter 1989), which was completed by siblings and parents.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_OUTCOMES>
<CHAR_NOTES>
<P>Power calculation: N/A.</P>
<P>The authors do not report the results of the two age-groups separately.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_NOTES>
</INCLUDED_CHAR>
<INCLUDED_CHAR MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:36:37 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" STUDY_ID="STD-Heiney-1990">
<CHAR_METHODS>
<P>Objectives: To evaluate the effects of a support group on the social adjustment of siblings of paediatric oncology patients.</P>
<P>Study design: non-randomised geographical (non-equivalent) control, pretest-posttest.</P>
<P>Recruitment: convenience sample.</P>
<P>Allocation: siblings living more than 60 miles from their sibling's treatment centre were allocated to the control group.</P>
<P>Informed consent: yes (from parents).</P>
<P>Total number <BR/>approached: not stated.</P>
<P>Number recruited: 14.</P>
<P>Method of analysis: An independent t-test was used to compare between group results. </P>
<P>Follow-up: not stated, probably 100%.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_METHODS>
<CHAR_PARTICIPANTS MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:30:50 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Country: USA.</P>
<P>Clinical setting: paediatric oncology centre.</P>
<P>Inclusions: siblings aged 9 to 15 years whose brothers or sisters were treated at a paediatric oncology clinic; and (1) who lived within a 60-mile radius of the treatment centre, and (2) whose parents agreed to participate in a concurrent parent group.</P>
<P>Exclusions: siblings living beyond a 60-mile radius of the treatment centre were excluded from the experimental group but were eligible for inclusion in the control group.</P>
<P>Healthy siblings of patients with common childhood cancers.</P>
<P>Age: not stated.</P>
<P>Gender: male n = 6, female n = 8.</P>
<P>Ethnicity: not stated.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<CHAR_INTERVENTIONS MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:36:37 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Aims: not stated.</P>
<P>I (n = 7): participated in a closed support group. Each of 7 sessions focused on a specific topic selected by the researchers from those identified as common concerns of siblings of children with cancer. The therapists used techniques to enhance the group processes described by <LINK REF="REF-Yalom-1983" TYPE="REFERENCE">Yalom 1983</LINK>. Cotherapists included specialists in child psychiatry and a paediatric nurse practitioner.</P>
<P>
<BR/>C (n = 7): Participants had no structured contact with the treatment centre staff.</P>
<P>N = (baseline) 14.</P>
<P>Theoretical basis: group psychotherapy (<LINK REF="REF-Yalom-1983" TYPE="REFERENCE">Yalom 1983</LINK>).<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_INTERVENTIONS>
<CHAR_OUTCOMES MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:31:15 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Timing of outcome assessment: baseline assessment before the beginning of the group; follow-up assessment at the end of the 7, 1-hour sessions (timing of control group not stated).</P>
<P>Coping, adjustment and wellbeing:<BR/>social adjustment was measured using the Social Adjustment Scale - Self Report (<LINK REF="REF-Weissman-1976" TYPE="REFERENCE">Weissman 1976</LINK>). Only 2 areas (peer relations and family) were used out of 6 covered by the scale.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_OUTCOMES>
<CHAR_NOTES>
<P>Power calculation: N/A</P>
<P>In view of the discrepancy between the experimental and descriptive data, the study authors suggest that "the quantitative measurement tool used may not have tapped the therapeutic benefits of participating in a support group. The benefits may have been delayed".<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_NOTES>
</INCLUDED_CHAR>
<INCLUDED_CHAR MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:32:18 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" STUDY_ID="STD-Houtzager-2001">
<CHAR_METHODS MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:31:40 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Objective: To evaluate the effects of a program involving supportive groups aimed at enhancing feelings of control in order to reduce anxiety in the siblings of children with cancer</P>
<P>Study design: uncontrolled before and after</P>
<P>Recruitment: Siblings and parents were informed about the group by letter. The families of children who are treated of have been treated at the Emma Kinderziekenhuis of the Academic Medical Centre in Amsterdam, and who are known to have siblings aged 7 to 18, receive an invitation for the sibling support group.</P>
<P>Allocation: 1st treatment group: Ill sibling being treated for the first time or in remission of first treatment, no relapse. 2nd treatment group: The non-remission group consists of six children (25%) who had a relapse before or during group participation of the sibling or who had a &#8216;stable disease&#8217;</P>
<P>Informed consent: Siblings and parents informed about the study by letter. Explicit informed consent not mentioned.</P>
<P>Total number approached: 38 siblings who participated in the support groups</P>
<P>Number agreed to participate: 24</P>
<P>Method of analysis: Analysis of pre and post questionnaires with State Trait Anxiety Inventory for Children (STAIC) to measure whether anxiety levels diminished after group participation. Paired samples t-test are performed with the total scores on the STAIC before and after group participation. T-tests were performed for the comparison of sibling mean anxiety scores before and after group participation with Dutch norms for children. The comparison with the normative data was executed for children and adolescents and for boys and girls separately. A regression analysis for differential anxiety scores was performed in order to investigate which characteristics of the sibling and of the ill child predict the effect of group participation.</P>
<P>Follow-up: No follow up</P>
</CHAR_METHODS>
<CHAR_PARTICIPANTS MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:32:07 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Country: Netherlands</P>
<P>Clinical setting: Academic Medical Centre in Amsterdam</P>
<P>Inclusions: 1st treatment group: Ill sibling being treated for the first time or in remission of first treatment, no relapse. 2nd treatment group: The non-remission group consists of six children (25%) who had a relapse before or during group participation of the sibling or who had a &#8216;stable disease&#8217;</P>
<P>Exclusions: Siblings who were excluded: only completed the questionnaire before the group; only completed the questionnaire after the group; completed none of the questionnaires; did not attend all group sessions. The excluded siblings did not differ from the other siblings in mean age and sex, nor were there any differences in type of diagnosis, time since diagnosis and survival perspective of the ill child.</P>
<P>Diagnosis of ill siblings: leukemia (n = 7), lymphoma (n = 4), solid tumors (n = 9), and brain tumors (n = 4). 13 were still in active treatment (54.2%).</P>
<P>Age: 7 to 18 years old (M 11.3; SD = 3.13),</P>
<P>Gender: nine boys (37.5%) and 15 girls (62.5%)</P>
<P>Ethnicity: not stated</P>
</CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<CHAR_INTERVENTIONS MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:32:11 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Aims: to enhance feelings of control in the participants in order to reduce their feelings of anxiety.</P>
<P>The intervention is a structured group, consisting of five weekly sessions led by psychologists, heterogeneous in nature, with respect to age and with respect to, diagnosis and treatment phase.</P>
<P>Theoretical basis: By increasing the siblings' knowledge and understanding of family relations, emotional reactions and of their sibling's illness and treatment, by clarifying misunderstandings, and by sharing experiences and emotions, their anxiety may be reduced (Last 1998).</P>
</CHAR_INTERVENTIONS>
<CHAR_OUTCOMES MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:32:18 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Timing of outcome assessment: Questionnaire completed before and after the 5 week program. Exact timing (i.e. number of weeks/days before and after) not stated. It is stated that; siblings were asked to fill out a questionnaire at home before and after group participation.</P>
<P>Coping, adjustment and wellbeing: In order to measure whether anxiety levels diminished after group participation, a paired samples t-test was performed with the total scores on the STAIC before and after group participation. A regression analysis for differential anxiety was performed in order to investigate which charateristics of the sibling and of the ill child could predict group participation. The measure for anxiety was the State Trait Anxiety Inventory for Children (STAIC ). The siblings' anxiety was assessed with the Dutch version of the STAIC (Spielberger 1973), translated by Bakker et al. (1989). In the analyses, a significance level of p &lt; 0.05 was required.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_OUTCOMES>
<CHAR_NOTES>
<P>Power calculation: N/A</P>
</CHAR_NOTES>
</INCLUDED_CHAR>
<INCLUDED_CHAR MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:36:38 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" STUDY_ID="STD-Sahler-1989">
<CHAR_METHODS MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:32:27 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Objective: To evaluate the effects of a 5-day residential camping program on 1) siblings' knowledge and understanding of their sibling's cancer, 2) siblings' perception of how the cancer experience has affected them (perceptions of disease influence) and 3) siblings' mood state.</P>
<P>Study design: before and after.</P>
<P>Recruitment: All siblings between the ages of 6 and 17 years with a brother or sister treated at any of the upstate New York paediatric oncology centres were invited to attend, regardless of whether their brother or sister was still in active treatment or still alive. Potential subjects consisted of all siblings registering for the camp during the first summer of evaluation and all new campers registering the next summer.</P>
<P>Allocation: N/A</P>
<P>Informed consent: yes, camper and parent(s).</P>
<P>Total number approached: 150</P>
<P>Number agreed to participate: 141</P>
<P>Method of analysis: Chi-square test and paired t-tests (one tailed) were used to analyse siblings' responses to the questionnaire before and after attending camp.</P>
<P>Follow-up: 64%</P>
</CHAR_METHODS>
<CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<P>Country: USA</P>
<P>Clinical setting: B&amp;ST (Brothers and Sisters Together) 5-day residential camp programme.</P>
<P>Inclusions: siblings between the ages of 6 and 17 years with a brother or sister treated at any of the upstate New York paediatric oncology centres. Only data on siblings whose brother or sister was still alive, are reported.</P>
<P>Exclusions: none stated.</P>
<P>Diagnosis: Healthy siblings or patients with the following diagnoses: leukaemia (50%), solid tumour (20%), lymphoma (15%), brain tumour (15%).</P>
<P>Age: 6 to 17 years (mean 11.2).</P>
<P>Gender: male: 51%, female 49%.</P>
<P>Ethnicity: not stated.</P>
</CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<CHAR_INTERVENTIONS MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:32:57 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Aims: to give siblings the opportunity to know more about their sibling's cancer and to be able to interact with peers in a similar situation and with professional staff experienced in counselling.</P>
<P>To assess the effect of repeated instruction on siblings' medical information, campers were grouped (a) according to whether they had previously attendedthe camping programme (new or return), and (b) into younger (6- to 11-years) and older (12- to 17-years) groups. This produced four groups: younger-returning campers (n = 15), younger-new campers (n = 33), older-returning campers (n=26) and older-new campers (n = 16). Recreation is the major component of Camp B&amp;ST but the camp is designed to provide siblings with medical information and peer support. Each camper attended a small-group 1-hour medical information session, led by a paediatric oncologist and an oncology nurse specialist. In order to provide age-appropriate instruction, campers were divided into 2 age groups (6 to 11 and 12 to 17). The sessions were experiential seminars and included opportunities to see and handle medical equipment and to ask questions. Various medical terms (eg. blood counts), procedures (eg. spinal tap) and therapies (eg. chemotherapy) were defined and simulated, and their function in the management of childhood cancer explained.</P>
<P>Campers also attended a group psychosocial support session. Groups were composed of campers of similar ages and further divided into groups of campers whose ill sibling was still alive and campers who were bereaved. Sessions were preceded by skits, staged by a theatre group, depicting common themes in families with childhood cancer (eg. parents not having time to attend a school play with a healthy sibling). Following each vignette, "in character" discussions to clarify feelings occurred between the actors and the audience.</P>
<P>N = (baseline) 141.</P>
<P>Theoretical basis: For sibling perception and adaptation to childhood cancer, the Family systems model for conceptualising sibling adaptation to chronic illness (McCubbin 1983).</P>
</CHAR_INTERVENTIONS>
<CHAR_OUTCOMES MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:36:38 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>ngs' fear of catching their brother's or sister's cancer, the study found 3/4 scores to be statistically signifcant. The paired t-test p values for the change in scores before and after are: 0.38, 0.01, 0.08 and 0.08. The authors' interpretation of these results is questionable, as only the 0.01 p value appears to indicate a statistically significant change.</P>
<P>Risk of bias table </P>
