<INCLUDED_CHAR MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:33:07 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" STUDY_ID="STD-Williams-1997">
<CHAR_METHODS>
<P>Objective: To evaluate the effects of an educational and support group intervention for siblings of children with chronic illness, including cancer, on knowledge and perceptions.</P>
<P>Study design: before and after.</P>
<P>Recruitment: convenience sample.</P>
<P>Allocation: N/A</P>
<P>Informed consent: consent form signed by parents and assent form signed by children.</P>
<P>Total number <BR/>approached: 29.</P>
<P>Number recruited: 22.</P>
<P>Method of analysis: paired t-test.</P>
<P>Follow-up: not stated, probably 100%.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_METHODS>
<CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<P>Country: USA.</P>
<P>Clinical setting: university affiliated medical centre.</P>
<P>Inclusions: siblings of children with diagnoses of cancer (6), cystic fibrosis (5), diabetes (2), or spina bifida (7).</P>
<P>Exclusions: not stated.</P>
<P>Age: 8 to 15 years (mean = 8.5).</P>
<P>Gender: male = 9, female = 13.</P>
<P>Ethnicity: Caucasian = 18, African-American = 3.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_PARTICIPANTS>
<CHAR_INTERVENTIONS MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:33:07 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor">
<P>Aims: not stated.</P>
<P>The intervention consisted of structured educational and support group sessions (number of sessions not stated). The intervention had 3 components: educational, psychosocial, and social/recreational. An average of 9 hours spent on the sibling sessions.</P>
<P>For the educational component (total 5-6 hours), information about each of the four diagnostic conditions was presented in separate rooms simultaneously. The content included the characteristics of the illness and its management in the hospital and at home.</P>
<P>For the psychosocial component (total 3-4 hours), group sessions were conducted with the whole group using materials from the Sibshop handbook (<LINK REF="REF-Meyer-1985" TYPE="REFERENCE">Meyer 1985</LINK>). These sessions included scenarios about common sibling experiences and problems. Group discussions focused on identifying the problem in each scenario, relating the story to personal issues and creating solutions.</P>
<P>The social and recreational component (total 1.5 hours) was interspersed with the group sessions as a form of distraction and to foster bonding between sibling and parent. Active group games (basketball), and table or board games were held with the whole group.</P>
<P>In addition, one 3-hour parent group session was held simultaneously with one of the sibling sessions. The main purpose of the session was to develop and enhance parental awareness of sibling needs.</P>
<P>N = (baseline) 22</P>
<P>Theoretical basis: not stated.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_INTERVENTIONS>
<CHAR_OUTCOMES>
<P>Timing of outcome assessment: prior to and immediately after the intervention.</P>
<P>Knowledge and understanding: measured by the Knowledge of Illness Test (developed for this study)</P>
<P>Coping, adjustment and wellbeing: sibling perceptions were measured by the Sibling Perception Questionnaire (SPQ; Sahler &amp; Carpenter, 1989): administered at baseline only.<BR/>
</P>
</CHAR_OUTCOMES>
<CHAR_NOTES>
<P>Power calculation: N/A.</P>
</CHAR_NOTES>
