<COMPARISON ID="CMP-001" MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:26:24 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" NO="1">
<NAME>Camping programme: before versus after</NAME>
<OTHER_OUTCOME COLS="3" ID="CMP-001.01" MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:26:24 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" NO="1" ROWS_PER_STUDY="1" SORT_BY="STUDY" STUDIES="1" SUBGROUPS="NO">
<NAME>Knowledge and understanding</NAME>
<TR>
<TH/>
<TH/>
<TH/>
</TR>
<OTHER_DATA MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:26:24 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" ORDER="1" STUDY_ID="STD-Sahler-1989">
<TR>
<TD>
<P>Medical knowledge and understanding were assessed by the Sibling Questionnaire (Sahler 1989). <BR/>(1)<BR/>Identification: improvement in two out of eight (25%) items (p&lt;0.02). Statistically significant increases in 'identification of procedures and therapies' were found for younger-returning campers and for older-new campers.<BR/>
<BR/>Instrumental: improvement in two out of eight (25%) items (p&lt;0.01). Statistically significant increases in instrumental understanding were found for younger-returning campers and older-new campers.</P>
</TD>
<TD>
<P>(2) The assessment of siblings' fear of catching their brother's or sister's cancer revealed low mean intensities of fear of contagion at pre-test in all four camper groups (for three out of four camper groups mean scores were less than 1 out of a possible range of 0-4). <BR/>
<BR/>The mean scores of younger-returning campers' fear of catching their brother's or sister's cancer showed a statistically significant reduction at post-test: from 1.27 (SD 1.49) to 0.47 (SD 0.92), p=0.01.</P>
</TD>
<TD>
<P>(3) The assessment of siblings' concern associated with their friends' worry about catching their brother's or sister's cancer also revealed low mean intensities of fear in all camper groups (4/4 camper group mean scores were less than 1 out of a possible range of 0-4). Statistically significant changes at post-test were found for two camper groups: the older-new camper group mean score reduced from 0.63 (SD 0.89) to 0.19 (SD 0.40), p=0.04, whereas the younger-returning camper group mean score increased from 0.53 (SD 0.92) to 1.20 (SD 1.21), p=0.03.</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</OTHER_DATA>
</OTHER_OUTCOME>
<OTHER_OUTCOME COLS="3" ID="CMP-001.02" MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:26:02 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" NO="2" ROWS_PER_STUDY="1" SORT_BY="STUDY" STUDIES="1" SUBGROUPS="NO">
<NAME>Coping, adjustment and wellbeing</NAME>
<TR>
<TH/>
<TH/>
<TH/>
</TR>
<OTHER_DATA MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:26:02 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" ORDER="2" STUDY_ID="STD-Sahler-1989">
<TR>
<TD>
<P>Perceptions and affective responses were assessed by the Sibling Questionnaire (Carpenter and Sahler). Interpersonal: improvement in 17% of items (NS).<BR/>Intrapersonal: improvement in 7/7 (100%) items (p&lt;0.00).<BR/>Communication: improvement in 1/4 (25%) items (NS).<BR/>Fear of disease: improvement in 1/3 (33%) items (p&lt;0.09).</P>
</TD>
<TD>
<P>Current mood state: assessed by the Parent Questionnaire (Carpenter and Sahler). Positive: improvement in 2/8 (25%) of items (p&lt;0.05). Negative: improvement in 4/6 (67%) of items (p&lt;0.00).</P>
</TD>
<TD>
<P>Current mood state: assessed by the Sibling Questionnaire: <BR/>Positive: improvement in 3/8 (38%) items (p&lt;0.02).<BR/>Negative: improvement in 4/6 (67%) items (p&lt;0.00).</P>
</TD>
</TR>
