<OTHER_OUTCOME COLS="2" ID="CMP-002.02" MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:27:01 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" NO="2" ROWS_PER_STUDY="1" SORT_BY="STUDY" STUDIES="3" SUBGROUPS="NO">
<NAME>Coping, adjustment and wellbeing</NAME>
<TR>
<TH/>
<TH/>
</TR>
<OTHER_DATA MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:27:01 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" ORDER="5" STUDY_ID="STD-Dolgin-1997">
<TR>
<TD>
<P>Feelings and attitudes were assessed by the Feelings and Attitudes Questionnaire (Sahler 1989). Interpersonal Problems: before=16.04 (SD 5.76), after=11.39 (SD 4.95; p&lt;0.001).<BR/>Intrapsychic Preoccupation: before=9.77 (SD 3.51), after=5.63 (SD 2.45; p&lt;0.000).<BR/>Disease-Related Communication: before=6.52 (SD 2.34), after=8.26 (SD 3.59; p&lt;0.001).<BR/>Fear: before=0.96 (SD 1.27), after=0.96 (SD 1.27; p=NS).<BR/>
</P>
</TD>
<TD>
<P>Mood was assessed by the Mood Questionnaire (Sahler and Carpenter 1989). Sibling-Report: before=3.22 (SD 11.00), after=14.78 (SD 6.75; p&lt;0.000).<BR/>Parent-Report, before=-3.43 (SD 10.39), after=18.19 (SD 6.92; p&lt;0.000).<BR/>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</OTHER_DATA>
<OTHER_DATA MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:27:01 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" ORDER="6" STUDY_ID="STD-Heiney-1990">
<TR>
<TD>
<P>Social adjustment was assessed by the Social Adjustment Scale - Self Report (Weissman and Bothwell 1976). No statistically significant mean before/after differences were found between the intervention and control groups.<BR/>
<BR/>No within-group differences between baseline and follow-up were reported.</P>
</TD>
<TD/>
</TR>
</OTHER_DATA>
<OTHER_DATA MODIFIED="2008-07-08 15:27:01 +1000" MODIFIED_BY="Megan Prictor" ORDER="7" STUDY_ID="STD-Houtzager-2001">
<TR>
<TD>
<P>Anxiety was measured by the State Trait Anxiety Inventory for Children (STAIC). The mean anxiety score before group participation (37.08) was significantly higher than after group participation (33.25) for the whole group of siblings (t =3,49; df 23; p 0.002). The majority of the siblings had high anxiety scores before group participation: 18 siblings (75%) had anxiety scores in the 8-10th decile. These reduced after group participation: 11 siblings (46%). Examination of changes in deciles showed: for 12 siblings (50%) there was a decrease in decile and for 11 siblings (46%), the decile score remains the same. One sibling (4%) had an increased decile score. <BR/>
<BR/>Before group participation, the boys as well as girls in the younger age group (7-12) and adolescent boys (13-18) had significantly higher mean anxiety scores than would be expected from the norms (p &lt; 0.05). For boys in both age groups, anxiety scores droped to a normal level again after group participation. For young girls, anxiety decreased after group participation, but remained significantly higher than in the norm group. For the adolescent girls, both before and after group participation, the level of anxiety experienced was comparable to that of their norm group.<BR/>
<BR/>T-tests showed that sibling age and the survival perspective of the ill child were not related to the differential anxiety scores. Time since diagnosis showed no significant correlation with the differential anxiety score (r =0.34; p 0.10; n 24). Type of diagnosis appeared to have a significant effect on the differential anxiety score in the regression analysis. The anxiety of siblings of children with leukemia or lymphoma decreased more after group participation than in siblings of children with a solid tumor or a brain tumor. There was no effect of being in or off treatment. Neither was in or off treatment a confounder for the effect of diagnosis.</P>
</TD>
<TD/>
</TR>
